The $y$-coordinate of the vertex of the parabola is $-1$.  The $x$-coordinates of the intersections of the line $y=r$ and the parabola are given by $x^2 - 1 = r$, or $x^2 = r + 1$.  Hence, the $y$-coordinates of these intersections are $r$.  The distance between these two points is $2 \sqrt{r}$ (using the distance formula), so the area of the triangle is
\[\frac{1}{2} \cdot 2 \sqrt{r} \cdot |r - (-1)| = \sqrt{r} |r + 1|.\]Thus, we want to find all values of $r$ such that
\[8 \le \sqrt{r} |r + 1| \le 64.\]If $r \ge 0$, then $|r + 1| = r + 1$, so we want
\[8 \le (r + 1) \sqrt{r} \le 64.\]Dividing by $\sqrt{r}$ (which is positive), we get
\[8 \sqrt{r} \le r + 1 \le 64 \sqrt{r}.\]If $r < -1$, then $|r + 1| = -(r + 1)$, so we want
\[8 \le -(r + 1) \sqrt{r} \le 64.\]Dividing by $-\sqrt{r}$ (which is positive), we get
\[8 \sqrt{r} \ge r + 1 \ge 64 \sqrt{r},\]or
\[r + 1 \le 8 \sqrt{r} \quad \text{and} \quad r + 1 \ge 64 \sqrt{r}.\]The left inequality is always true for $r < -1$, so we only need to consider the right inequality.  This simplifies to
\[64 \sqrt{r} - r - 1 \le 0.\]We plot the graphs of $y = 64 \sqrt{x} - x - 1$ and $y = 0$:

